As a poster, I prioritize boosters who have demonstrated loyalty and supported me during periods of low cuts . I will also select them during times of high cuts.

Connections/reputation have always been a part of every sort of hiring process independent of the context
It is perfectly normal and common to see someone who might look less qualified more successful due to their connections

In the context of boosting, a booster who has been active throughout the whole season doing high keys and building trust with posters will ALWAYS get prioritized over someone who didn't build the trust and only stayed active the first few weeks

In your point of view it might sound unreasonable to pick someone with 600 less IO than you, while the big picture is that those people already proved they are capable of doing difficult boosts regardless of their IO

Now, we keep saying this every single patch, even though we have nothing to do with the decision making process, but the same exact sort of conversation happens every patch for the first few weeks

If you want my opinion as someone who has access to data for years, I can say:
- If the demand is less than the number of "trusted" people, you basically have no chance. So high prices are NOT in your favor
- If the demand is slightly higher than the number of trusted people, then your IO is relevant and that the sweet spot for high IO people who want high cut
- If the demand is way higher than the number of trusted people, then it will be on the low cut zone and that's when you have the chance to build trust and become one of the trusted ones by the posters
Every season this pattern happens! Right now it's the first stage

Not pointing any fingers or smth, but when I see someone without a single key done for last 3 months of last season, it's very predictable that they are not going to get picked over someone  who has been actively doing 15s and 16s. You have IO, they have a long history of being trustworthy, guess who will be picked
